##Don't let the plague become a breeding ground for racism and regionalism

Micro Signal Directorbai

Function description, all my feelings are illuminated by the moonlight.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Today is January 29th, the 19% phase of the crescent moon.

It is January 29 with a 19 percent of Waxing Crescent.

The full moon is 11 days away.

There are 11 days until Full Moon.

| | Bai Qingyang

The reviews don't deserve the song

Without Looking, I thought I was back in the park in The Bund:

"No Chinese or dogs allowed. "

It's not historically true

I live in London. The outbreak is stable and no one has been confirmed. Chinese self-harvesting masks in stock. I went to the drugstore yesterday to buy hand sanitizer, and the clerk told me it was short. "The purchasing power of the Chinese is terrifying, " I texted my friend

I'm meeting with my advisor this morning to talk about my thesis. She's an expert in the history of the republic, studying comic books. She's a big, fat, cute British sister. After seeing me, she smiled at me: "Happy New Year! " And then said: "I feel extremely sad for those who are experiencing disaster. I hope they get well soon! "

I told her the Chinese would be fine. She believed me.

It's a rare day in London. The Sun hit the house, it seems to shine with the light of Western civilization, freedom and fraternity.

But the clouds are coming fast. I walked out of the office and spotted it with a familiar Hong Kong schoolmate. He grabbed me and said, "look at this video. It's funny. ".

The video went on to show how girls from Thailand, Uzbekistan and another country sneezed. Before I knew it, there was a Chinese girl in the video. She sneezed, and it was like a stampede in a subway station.

I ate it like a fly and left in a hurry.

(in the evening, I told the Hong Kong student online that I had been offended and he had apologized to me.)

I saw a news report yesterday. A Chinese boy was playing in Italy when a rival player told him, "may you catch a virus soon. " At the time, his coach, team-mates and referees gave no indication. He left the scene in tears and later posted on social media, lambasting his ordeal.

Today I saw the French "Le Courrier Picard" ("yellow alert") as the title, in the name of the plague in the name of blatant racism news. Although the story was pulled from its Web site, its impact was dire: Do you remember the word Yellow Peril?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Delta source see screenshot.

The word first became popular around the famous "boxer" Year: 1900. 120 years later, we are back in the year of the boxer rebellion, as if the world had never changed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Americans kick the horrid yellow peril aside.

An 1880 American soap advertisement headlined "The Chinese Must Go" .

By then, the term "yellow peril" had not been widely used, but discrimination (and fear) against East Asians, including the Japanese, had begun.

From the "fear of Hubei" in China to the "fear of China" in the world, the impact of the plague has far exceeded the disease itself and spread to the culture, society and International Relations. In the big picture of a global right turn, with "Clash of Civilizations" now in vogue, relations between countries, especially ordinary people, are already cooling rapidly; and with the help of external forces such as the plague, the illusion of a "global village" created by the world's century-long efforts will turn into a bubble in an instant.

Speaking of which, I'm just as useless here as calling for an end to discrimination. Posting on international social networks in a huff doesn't make much of a splash. Everyone has a reason. "We're not racist, we just don't want the French / Danes / Italians... to get infected, " he said, before proudly putting up a sign saying no Chinese or dogs.

How beautiful. The concept of "racism" was born in the west and was torn down with it. All along, the Chinese people have been "the other" , not worthy of voice, not worthy of speech.

The West has manipulated every word, and one of them has said something that discriminates against the Chinese (like Piers Morgan the other day, when a British television presenter was denounced online by the British for saying "ching-chong") , when the Western masters were happy, they helped us out by saying, "only the Chinese decide whether to be racist or not. " But when it came to plague discussions, they used discriminatory language, and said, "we're not racist. We're just... "

I don't care what "just" is. You didn't really care what we thought anyway, did you?

What is more terrible is that the victims of Orientalism Still Defend Orientalism. Read this:

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I'd love to hear who said it, but wechat is said to delete articles on the grounds of invasion of privacy, so be it. (and I still have the conscience of a writer.)

National surveillance of the virus, whether the information is transparent, the handling of the epidemic, and so on, are all important issues that deserve our attention. The country and the government have done wrong and we should criticize them. But that is no reason for the West to discriminate against China and its people.

Racial Discrimination can not be justified on any grounds.

I thought that was the accepted wisdom of the world from the second half of the 20th century.

I was naive.

I knew that if I wrote this, Westerners wouldn't see it, and my angry rants on the Internet wouldn't get their attention. But the world is so screwed up, I need at least a little space to speak my mind. You can't choke on words.

At the end of the article, I want to make an initiative.

I advocate that we can not control racism, or at least not transmit it inwards. We know that when spring comes, Wuhan's Cherry Blossoms are beautiful, Bai Yansong said on the show.

Dear friends from Hubei, we'll see you when the cherry blossoms bloom.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wuhan University Cherry Blossoms. (image: Network)

The world, we will also look forward to your better day.
